
[1]bark

   B'ARK, n. [Probably from stripping, separating.]

   1. The rind or exterior covering of a tree, corresponding to the skin
   of an animal. This is composed of the cuticle or epidermis, the outer
   bark or cortex, and the inner bark or liber. The rough broken matter on
   bark is, by the common people of New England, called ross.

                                     39

   2. By way of distinction. Peruvian Bark.

    B'ARK, v.t. To peel; to strip off bark. Also to cover or inclose with
                                    bark.

                                    B'ARK
